fields.title: LAPD Press Release Re: Crime Maps
fields.description: A release issued by the Los Angeles Police Department at a July 9, 2009 press conference. The statement was made in response to a story in that day's Los Angeles Times alleging that department's public crime mapping site, www.lapdcrimemaps.org, omitted nearly 40 percent of city crime. The Times summarized the press conference in two posts, one recording the police chief's discussion of the map, and another about the gathering's intended topic, a sweep of arrests made against the Toonerville street gang.

fields.title: David Simon, Jo Becker, Jim Schaefer
fields.description: Writer/producer David Simon, Jo Becker of The New York Times and Jim Schaefer of the Detroit Free Press, left to right, discuss "the art of source development" at the Investigative Reporters and Editors 2009 conference in Baltimore. Simon, a former reporter for The Baltimore Sun, is now perhaps best known for his role in the production of the HBO television series The Wire. During the discussion, Simon confessed to pretexting by withholding his identity as a reporter.
fields.tags: conference ire09 investigativereportersandeditors jimschaefer davidsimon jobecker thewire detroitfreepress sources newyorktimes journalist baltimore

fields.title: Joe Mahr, Thomas Peele, A.C. Thompson
fields.description: Joe Mahr of the St. Louis Post-Dispatch, Thomas Peele of Bay Area News and A.C. Thompson of ProPublica, left to right, discuss covering cops and courts at the Investigative Reporters and Editors 2009 conference in Baltimore. Peele and Thompson explained how they have pieced together detailed stories on unsolved crimes, including their award-winning investigation into the death of Oakland journalist Chauncey Bailey. Mahr explained how his team was able to use electronic records requests to document fraud and abuse in the local police department's towing operation.
fields.tags: conference ire09 investigativereportersandeditors thomaspeele bayareanews propublica crime chaunceybaileyproject joemahr stlouispostdispatch journalist chaunceybailey acthompson baltimore copsandcourts

fields.title: T. Christian Miller
fields.description: T. Christian Miller of ProPublica presents on how he refines the raw materials of reporting into an investigative story at the Investigative Reporters and Editors 2009 conference in Baltimore. Miller offered a number of recommendations for organization, including the use of a tablet computer and Microsoft One Note when taking notes at press conferences. He also advocated using Microsoft Excel to create a timeline of events before drafting a story so that the writer can search for narrative threads and better understand the chain of events. As an example, Miller referred to past stories on injured military contractors.
fields.tags: conference ire09 investigativereportersandeditors propublica baltimore journalist tchristianmiller

fields.title: Laura Frank
fields.description: Laura Frank presents on how she refines the raw materials of reporting into an investigative story at the Investigative Reporters and Editors 2009 conference in Baltimore. By way of example, Frank walked through the process of publishing her Rocky Mountain News series on the treatment of nuclear workers who claim to have been injured on the job.
fields.tags: conference ire09 investigativereportersandeditors laurafrank journalist baltimore

fields.title: Joe Mahr
fields.description:
Joe Mahr of the St. Louis Post-Dispatch explained how his team was able to use electronic records requests to document fraud and abuse in the local police department's towing operation.

Mahr was speaking at a panel on covering cops and courts at the Investigative Reporters and Editors 2009 conference in Baltimore.
fields.tags: conference ire09 investigativereportersandeditors joemahr stlouispostdispatch journalist baltimore

fields.title: Mark Benjamin
fields.description: Mark Benjamin of Salon.com narrates a videotape of a friendly fire death in Iraq released with his story Friendly Fire in Iraq -- and a coverup. During his presentation, Benjamin praised the value of conventional reporting techniques, such as building trust with primary witnesses and working nights so you can talk with sources outside of their workplaces, in environments where they're likely to be more comfortable speaking freely. Benjamin was speaking on the "Investigating casualties of war" panel at the Investigative Reporters and Editors 2009 conference in Baltimore.
fields.tags: conference ire09 investigativereportersandeditors journalism markbenjamin baltimore

fields.title: Michael Pell
fields.description: Michael Pell of The Center for Public Integrity explains how his team conducted their Perils of the New Pesticides investigation using a little-known database from the Environmental Protection Agency. Also pictured are Blake Morrison of USA Today, right, and John Sullivan of The Philadephia Inquirer, left, who joined Pell on the "Toxic trouble: Examining shortcomings in federal environmental regulation" panel at the Investigative Reporters and Editors 2009 conference in Baltimore.
fields.tags: conference ire09 investigativereportersandeditors journalism michaelpell baltimore
